gin": 1334, "end": 1338}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:4842"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "NOS enzymes", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9833739995956421, "span": {"begin": 1389, "end": 1400}}, {"id": ["mesh:D009569"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "NO", "obj": "drug", "prob": null, "span": {"begin": 1485, "end": 1487}}, {"id": ["mesh:D010900"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "endothelial dysfunction", "obj": "disease", "prob": 0.9998819231987, "span": {"begin": 1543, "end": 1566}}, {"id": ["mesh:D010900"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "endothelial dysfunction", "obj": "disease", "prob": 0.9999817609786987, "span": {"begin": 1635, "end": 1658}}, {"id": ["mesh:D009569"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "NO", "obj": "drug", "prob": null, "span": {"begin": 1673, "end": 1675}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:4843"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "iNOS", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.991058886051178, "span": {"begin": 1729, "end": 1733}}, {"id": ["mesh:D009569"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "NO", "obj": "drug", "prob": null, "span": {"begin": 1860, "end": 1862}}, {"id": ["mesh:D030421"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "peroxynitrite", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9984190464019775, "span": {"begin": 1879, "end": 1892}}, {"id": ["mesh:D009584"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "nitrogen", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9992889165878296, "span": {"begin": 1914, "end": 1922}}, {"id": ["mesh:D009569"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "NO", "obj": "drug", "prob": null, "span": {"begin": 2073, "end": 2075}}, {"id": ["CUI-less"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "senescent ECs", "obj": "cell_line", "prob": 0.9459376335144043, "span": {"begin": 2125, "end": 2138}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:4846"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "eNOS", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9916340112686157, "span": {"begin": 2180, "end": 2184}}, {"id": ["mesh:D009569"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "NO", "obj": "drug", "prob": null, "span": {"begin": 2219, "end": 2221}}, {"id": ["CUI-less"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "senescent ECs", "obj": "cell_line", "prob": 0.9137016534805298, "span": {"begin": 2291, "end": 2304}}, {"id": ["mesh:D010900"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "endothelial dysfunction", "obj": "disease", "prob": 0.9996401071548462, "span": {"begin": 2313, "end": 2336}}], "text": "The biological plausibility surrounding the connection between altered NO levels leading to endothelial dysfunction is well-supported by literature. NO is synthesized from L-arginine and oxygen with the aid of enzymes and cofactors (Nagane et al., 2021). NO regulates ECs by binding to soluble guanylyl cyclase (sGC) to create cGMP and activate protein kinase G (PKG), leading to activation of Ca2+-dependent vasodilation and smooth muscle relaxation (Nagane et al., 2021; Soloviev &amp; Kizub 2019). NOS isoforms, such as inducible NO synthase (iNOS) and endothelial NO synthase (eNOS) that synthesize NO are indirect measures of NO. Lower NO reduces the ability of SMCs relaxation and dilates the blood vessel leading to an inability to control vasodilation, a component of endothelial dysfunction (Soloviev &amp; Kizub 2019).&nbsp;  Increased expression of NOS enzymes can result in reduced NO levels in the case of insufficient L-arginine substrate or BH4 cofactor leading to ROS production instead of NO (Zhang et al., 2009). ROS can decrease NO bioavailability by uncoupling/downregulating eNOS or converting NO to peroxynitrite (Mitchel et al 2019; Schulz, Gori &amp; M&uuml;nzel, 2011; Soloviev &amp; Kizub 2019; Wang, Boerma &amp; Zhou, 2016). A further decrease in NO occurs as peroxynitrite oxidizes BH4 to BH2 and induces eNOS to produce ROS, continuing the uncoupling of more NOS enzymes (Hong et al., 2013; Soloviev &amp; Kizub, 2019; Zhang et al., 2009). A reduction in NO bioavailability due to ROS is an important mediator of endothelial dysfunction (Schulz, Gori &amp; M&uuml;nzel, 2011).&nbsp;  Another component of endothelial dysfunction influenced by NO levels is cellular senescence (Nagane et al., 2021). iNOS expression increases following an increase in oxidative stress (Nathan &amp; Xie, 1994). In the presence of oxidative stress, NO is converted to peroxynitrite, which is a reactive nitrogen species (RNS) that can modify proteins and lead to cellular senescence (Hong et al., 2013; Nagane et al., 2021; Soloviev &amp; Kizub, 2019). Although NO can increase at first and cause cell senescence, senescent ECs show downregulation and/or uncoupling of eNOS that contributes to a decrease of NO in the endothelium (Wang, Boerma &amp; Zhou, 2016). These changes in senescent ECs lead to endothelial dysfunction.&nbsp;", "timestamp": "Mon Jun 08 15:56:01 +0000 2026"}